<TEXT>
the philippine military admits that thousands of 
villages are heavily influenced by communist rebels associated 
press reporter yasmin arquiza visited one such village and here is 
her report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
with its huts 
scattered along steep slopes the village looks no different from 
hundreds of others in the rugged cordillera range but here village 
elders owe their allegiance to communist rebels 
residents say they began cooperating with the new peoples army 
to fill a void created by the lack of services from the central 
government in manila about 200 miles to the south 
members of the village council granted an interview to the 
associated press on condition that the name of the settlement not be 
published to avoid military reprisal 
the village in kalingaapayo province is near the town of 
balbalan and is among 10 in the area which is virtually controlled 
by the new peoples army the military admits that up to 20 percent 
of the 40000 villages nationwide are influenced by the 
insurgents 
in this village and several others nearby rebel influence 
amounts to virtual control 
experiences of the villagers offer insights into why the 
insurgency persists despite the 1986 ouster of president ferdinand 
marcos and the rise of a democratic administration under corazon 
aquino 
the 34yearold village leader who would not give his name 
traced the origin of the rebel government to a lack of confidence in 
the marcos administration 
he said villagers whose main contact with the central government 
is an occasional military patrol remain unconvinced that the new 
administration in manila is significantly different from the old 
we had no trust in our elected officials and we could not work 
in the fields due to intense militarization said the leader we 
wanted to find out the best way to solve these problems 
communist guerrillas began operating in the cordillera mountains 
of northern luzon in the early 1970s but arrived in this village 
only in 1982 more than three years before marcos was ousted 
the rebels conducted political seminars taught villagers to read 
and write and then established camps nearby they improved living 
conditions by running off thieves and campaigning against alcohol 
and gambling all of which had flourished due to inadequate police 
protection 
those who did not want to cooperate with the rebels were warned 
to leave on nov 14 1987 the rebels de facto control was 
formalized when residents nominated and elected a rival village 
council which works with the local insurgent commander 
the rebel village council operates in tandem with the 
governments sevenmember local committee in some cases residents 
serve openly on the government council and secretly on the rebel 
panel 
the village leader said the presence of rebel sympathizers on the 
official town council enables the underground committee to control 
and monitor funds earmarked for the area by provincial and national 
governments 
the mayor is reduced to a figurehead said a local new 
peoples army leader who gave his name only as ka comrade 
dangkas 
the village leader boasted that the underground administration 
has been more successful in implementing development projects he 
recalled that in 1979 local officials of marcos new society 
movement party wasted so much money in constructing a school that 
there was not enough cash left to build a floor 
by contrast the village leader said the rebel council has 
encouraged residents to plant vegetables to reduce their economic 
dependence on coffee production 
residents say they have accepted the authority of the shadow 
government because its members were chosen freely by secret ballot 
members of the official council are largely holdovers from the 
marcos administration 
the aquino government plans to hold its first village election 
next march 
still the rebels hold on the village faces threats from the 
military and the rival cordillera peoples liberation army which 
broke with the new peoples army in 1986 and cooperates with the 
government 
a few months ago the rival rebels killed a village council 
member and another civilian in a nearby municipality because they 
were suspected of aiding the communists the village leader said 
he also said the rebels has tried to flush out communist 
supporters in his village 
everybody knows who we are the village leader said of rebel 
supporters but so far he said villagers have refused to expose 
them 
</TEXT>
