<TEXT>
no one told richard green it would be easy when 
he took over in march as chancellor of the nations biggest school 
system 
in rapid succession greens school system with nearly 1 million 
students has had to contend with allegations of drug use political 
and sexual payoffs theft of school property and other abuses by 
educators and administrators 
a principal was charged with buying crack on a harlem street 
school officials are alleged to have used cocaine at meetings a 
high school student brought a semiautomatic weapon to class a 
school board member was alleged to have kept a baby grand piano 
belonging to the school in his home and a school aide claimed she 
was transferred against her will after she rejected a board members 
offer to go skinnydipping and make beautiful music together 
those allegations come on top of the systems entrenched 
problems uncooperative legislators high dropout rates drug use 
crumbling buildings disgruntled employees and abandonment of the 
schools by middleclass white students 
then there are such horror stories as elementary classes forced 
to meet in bathrooms because of a lack of classroom space and high 
school students relying on 30yearold textbooks 
here on the toughest turf in american education green 52 has 
responded much as he did during his seven years as school 
superintendent in minneapolis with an approach that is lowkey and 
methodical and a style that is blunt and acerbic 
green has resisted easy answers to difficult problems has 
reacted sharply to those who have criticized him for not moving fast 
enough and has resolutely refused to blow his own horn 
but he did step in and suspend the board of one district in the 
bronx after an investigation turned up evidence of patronage 
extortion and misuse of public money 
during a tv interview broadcast sunday green said he would not 
hesitate to suspend other boards if a report due monday from the 
central board of educations inspector general indicated widespread 
corruption in a district 
asked in august what he considered his greatest accomplishments 
he replied none i havent accomplished anything ive come to 
set the stage for making education work 
while critics have wondered when the play would begin green has 
been busy behind the scenes tinkering with the bureaucracy moving 
to tighten discipline in the schools and negotiating with the 
legislature for greater power over principals and the community 
school boards that runs the citys elementary and middle schools 
green who is paid 150000 a year became the first black 
chancellor of new york citys school system after a bitter selection 
process that pitted him the favorite of the teachers union 
green was the favorite of mayor edward koch and school board 
president robert f wagner jr at greens swearingin koch promised 
green that the mayor and other local officials would be nothing more 
than soldiers in your army 
but koch is nobodys soldier as became clear recently when green 
urged compassion instead of condemnation of the principal charged 
with buying crack 
koch and wagner angrily said green should have made an example of 
the principal green ultimately reversed his stand 
speaking of koch and wagner he said i certainly do 
acknowledge that their perceptions on how to market issues in the 
city may be more advanced than mine 
in fact green has shown an unwillingness to market issues in 
the nations mass media capital and has kept a low profile for most 
of his tenure 
critics say he has missed an opportunity to capture the publics 
interest and focus attention on the schools 
anybody with any brains will know youre not going to turn the 
schools around in a day said school board member edward sadowsky 
but the public requires and has a right to require some signs that 
something is happening 
lately things have been happening but they havent been good 
prosecutors are said to be investigating the shooting death of a 
harlem school board employee the man died in april reportedly just 
before he was to testify before a grand jury investigating 
allegations of corruption against the board 
bronx district attorney paul gentile said his investigators were 
looking into charges that bronx school board members demanded sex in 
exchange for jobs or promotions 
green said in a recent tv interview that those who would write 
his political obituary now are very premature 
i believe even those that have judged me will someday find 
things that we are doing that they can be proud of he said and 
i dont ask them to have patience i ask them to simply keep your 
eye on the prize and thats the children of the city and expect 
the chancellor will be the no 1 cheerleader for them 
</TEXT>
