<TEXT>
president roh taewoo named a new 
cabinet today in atonement for the harsh rule of his predecessor 
but the opposition rejected the shakeup and charged that some new 
ministers had supported dictatorship 
by naming kang younghoon prime minister and installing 19 new 
ministers roh was attempting to defuse nationwide furor over the 
government of former president chun doohwan and show his commitment 
to democratic reform 
but the new 23member cabinet consists mainly of appointees from 
the governing democratic justice party there were no dramatic 
changes and key law intelligence and military posts went to 
officials who served under chun 
a government statement said the changes were to put the mind of 
the public at rest following the anxiety created by problems of the 
past era and that the new cabinet would ensure further 
democratic reforms 
roh had promised a shakeup after appealing nov 26 to the nation 
for mercy for chun 
opposition parties said today that roh had not fulfilled promises 
to end ties with chuns authoritarian government and opposition 
leaders voiced doubt about rohs willingness to repudiate chun 
we are surprised that the new cabinet includes persons who 
actively supported dictatorship said lee sangsoo spokesman of 
the main opposition party for peace and democracy 
the reunification democratic party the other main opposition 
party also criticized rohs shuffle we are skeptical about the 
governments intention to liquidate the chun government said 
party spokesman suh chongwon 
opposition leaders said they would oppose the appointment of the 
new prime minister because roh had violated the constitution by 
failing to first consult the national assembly on the choice 
dissident groups which have organized a series of violent 
protests in recent weeks to demand chuns arrest and rohs 
overthrow dismissed the cabinet changes as a deception to continue 
militarybacked rule 
it seemed unlikely the changes would have a major impact on 
public opinion or diminish widespread demands for strong action 
against chun south korean cabinets traditionally have little 
authority and most of the ministers dismissed today were relatively 
unknown 
chun a former general who took power with military backing in 
1980 and stepped down as president in february went into internal 
exile last month after apologizing to the nation for corruption and 
human rights abuses 
roh also an exgeneral and former chun ally has attempted to 
defuse the crisis over demands for retribution against chun by 
shaking up the government releasing political prisoners and 
compensating victims of chuns rule 
roh who won presidential elections last december against a 
divided opposition is opposed to punishing chun but he must settle 
the crisis without damaging the credibility of his government which 
is still closely identified with chun 
among major appointments lee handong who ran the governing 
under chun was named home minister with control of the police huh 
hyongkoo a former prosecutorgeneral under chun was named justice 
minister and career diplomat choi hojoong was named foreign 
minister 
three ministers from the old cabinet were retained 
despite earlier government hints that a civilian would be named 
to head the key defense ministry former general lee sanghoon was 
picked lee filled top military posts under chun 
roh named olympic games organizer park sehjik to head the 
nations main intelligence agency the agency for national security 
planning park is a former general and was deputy chief of the 
agency under chun 
prime minister kang a relatively unknown lawmaker has served as 
ambassador to britain and the holy see he was forced out of the 
military in 1961 after opposing a military coup headed by former 
president park chunghee 
kang then obtained a doctorate in political science at southern 
california university 
chun who went into exile at a remote buddhist monastery after 
apologizing to the nation for abuses under his rule has denied any 
personal corruption some of his relatives and associates have been 
covicted of or charged with embezzlement and other crimes 
the main opposition parties have said there can be no question of 
a pardon for chun until after he has cooperated with a major 
national assembly probe into widespread abuses under his 
administration 
