<DOCNO> AP881205-0059 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fifty years after it first arrived on broadway 
thornton wilders our town remains an unexpectedly vibrant 
often surprising piece of theater 
thats pretty amazing considering how wellknown the play is 
there probably isnt a drama club high school college playhouse or 
community theater where the story of life in grovers corners nh 
hasnt been told 
that sense of vibrancy permeates a sterling new production of 
our town its the work of the lincoln center theater company 
which opened the play sunday at broadways lyceum theater the 
darkly burnished revival directed by the companys artistic guru 
gregory mosher is straightforward and unsentimental but it doesnt 
sacrifice honest emotion 
our town is a meditation on life quite serious and even 
somber particularly in its third act when it deals with life after 
death but thats not what most people remember about the play 
usually its bathed in nostalgia for the past an uncomplicated 
turnofthe century america where people didnt lock their doors at 
night where the milkman still delivered milk to your doorstep and 
where young lovers could get engaged over a strawberry phosphate at 
the local drug store 
those details are in this production but thats just what they 
are only details in the larger story of life in our town we 
like to know the facts about everybody says the stage manager 
the nameless narrator who tells the story of grovers corners and 
the people who live there its these facts pleasant and 
unpleasant that make the picture whole 
wilder divides his play into three acts the first called 
daily life introduces the characters of our town 
particularly the gibbs and webb families its their children 
george gibbs and emily webb who marry and whose story becomes the 
second act love and marriage 
theres no title for act iii i reckon you can guess what 
thats about says the stage manager it deals with death 
specifically emilys death in childbirth the scenes are played 
simply yet the sparseness of the emotion makes it all the more 
affecting 
mosher has been fastidious in his casting of the large company 
nearly 30 actors in all the narrator is playe here by spalding 
gray gray best known as the author and star of his own monologues 
including swimming to cambodia is a sardonic storyteller 
theres an edge to his performance that slices the sweetness of some 
of the events happening on stage 
penelope ann miller and eric stoltz turn the sometimes cloying 
young lovers into believable human beings miss miller in 
particular handles the transition from innocence to experience with 
a touching directness 
frances conroy james rebhorn roberta maxwell and peter maloney 
are fine as the quartet of parents offering individual portraits in 
roles that are often considered no more than supporting miss conroy 
is eerily effective as the other worldly mrs gibbs who loses all 
interest in what was her life after she has passed on 
mosher also gets strong support from an excellent production 
team jane greenwoods costumes are stylish yet subdued 
monochromatic outfits that dont call attention to themselves yet 
seem exactly right equally commendable is kevin rigdons sensitive 
lighting and douglas steins few chairs and tables strewn across a 
bare playing area 
theres a magical almost mystical quality to this production of 
our town maybe thats because its performed on the large empty 
stage of a broadway theater intricate patterns of pipes cover the 
back brick wall of the lyceum and an enormous system of lights seems 
to climb to the sky 
its a haunting environment for a haunting production told with 
a style and simplicity that reconfirms our towns reputation as 
an american classic 
in other reviews the new york times frank rich pointed to one 
major casting miscalculation spalding grays flip stage manager 
that constantly disrupts the fragile text the firm staging and the 
otherwise wellchosen cast the attempt through mr gray to 
turn the playwright into something hes not derails mr moshers 
our town 
while it would no doubt be sickening to see a stage manager 
resembling the lovable old codgers in winecooler commercials mr 
gray swings too far the other way presenting the narrator as if he 
were a narcissistic newwave raconteur exactly matching the 
storyteller in his own autobiographical performance pieces 
clive barnes of the new york post wrote gray is altogether too 
contemporary and too removed from the middle america of the first 
decades of the century what makes the version glow and what 
will forever be remembered about it are the two young people 
these two lit up the stage with truth honesty and unexpected 
tragedy as a village romeo and juliet 
and howard kissel wrote in the daily news the tone of gregory 
moshers production though full of lively ideas often seems too 
casual it misses the gravity of turnofthecentury life when 
grownups felt compelled to act as such but the play is 
actorproof even nonactorproof since spalding gray as the stage 
manager confirms my feeling that avantegarde performers are not 
really actors 
</TEXT>
