minister pik botha was quoted as saying 
cuban angolan and congolese officials were reported angry 
disillusioned and embarrassed by the departure saturday night of 
botha and the south african delegation following four days of talks 
in congo 
the session produced no signed agreement on a procedure for 
withdrawal of 50000 cuban troops from angola and implementation of 
an independence plan for southwest africa which is ruled by south 
africa 
but botha sounded optimistic sunday in interviews reported by the 
independent south african press association and the governmentrun 
radio south africa 
the process is irreversible he said we continue to 
progress stepbystep the radio quoted him as saying the talks 
could be resumed within a few days and a protocol signing is 
still a possibility 
sapa reported that the south african decision to leave was made 
by president pw botha who had been sent a copy of a draft 
protocol but apparently wanted further discussions 
sapa quoted the foreign minister who is not related to the 
president as saying the talks in brazzaville resulted in some 
progress but the cabinet needed time to assess the situation 
cubas viceminister for foreign affairs ricardo de quesada 
said if the south africans were truly for peace in angola and 
independence in namibia they would not have employed this 
diplomatic ruse namibia is another name for southwest africa 
de quesada said in brazzaville that the diplomats had been so 
close to agreement the text had already been typed and he said the 
south africans insulted everyone 
the major stumbling block for the south africans is the method 
for verifying that the cuban troops which have been supporting the 
marxist government in angola since 1976 withdraw according to an 
agreed schedule 
their departure from southern africa is a necessity as far as 
south africa is concerned because of fears that their presence 
might favor a takeover in southwest africa by the southwest 
african peoples organization 
that group has been fighting more than two decades against south 
african control of southwest africa 
