the supreme court today refused to revive a 
70000 award to a tennessee woman who said her rights had been 
violated in a dispute with public school officials over godless 
textbooks 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by vicki frost a 
christian fundamentalist briefly arrested for refusing to leave 
school grounds during an attempt to remove her daughter from a 
reading class 
mrs frost of rogersville was among seven tennessee familes who 
objected to textbooks approved by the hawkins county board of 
education 
the supreme court last february denied an earlier appeal by the 
families essentially ending a case some had called scopes ii a 
reference to the furor surrounding the 1925 prosecution of john 
scopes in tennessee for teaching evolution 
the justices let stand a ruling that requiring children to read 
books their parents objected to does not violate the families 
constitutional rights 
the case acted on today involved a separate civil rights suit by 
mrs frost stemming from the dispute 
mrs frost a mother of three was allowed for a time in 1983 to 
remove her daughter sarah from a reading class at church hill 
elementary school 
school officials permitted mrs frost to take sarah to the 
schools library or cafeteria for a reading lesson from books mrs 
frost approved 
she objected to the schools textbooks which she said taught 
secular humanism evolution and other beliefs she considered 
godless 
school officials changed their policy in november 1983 and no 
longer permitted mrs frost to remove sarah from the classroom for 
individual instruction 
mrs frost objected to the new policy and was jailed for about 
three hours on nov 23 1983 when she refused to leave the school 
premises after being ordered to by the school principal 
a jury awarded her 70000 in a federal lawsuit charging school 
officials with false imprisonment malicious prosecution violation 
of her freespeech rights and deprivation of the custody of her 
child 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals threw out the award last 
july 
the appeals court said her claims are without merit the 
appeals court said mrs frost was aware she no longer would be able 
to remove sarah from class and had an unencumbered freedom to 
put sarah in a private school a move she made in december 1983 
but rather than transfer sarah immediately frost chose to send 
her daughter back to church hill elementary and renew her disruption 
of the schools normal routine the appeals court said 
the evidence points so strongly in favor of school officials 
that we think reasonable minds could not come to a different 
conclusion the appeals court said 
the case is frost vs hawkins county board 88604 
