the supreme court today barred a new hampshire 
community from removing poles bearing sirens that could alert 
townspeople about an accident at the controversial seabrook nuclear 
power plant 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that limits the 
power of cities to revoke licenses for the poles 
public service of new hampshire major owner of seabrook is 
required by the nuclear regulatory commission to develop an 
emergency evacuation plan in case of an accident at the plant 
the utility company installed sirens placed on poles in several 
seacoast communities including rye nh 
the poles are about 60 feet high with sirens weighing about 500 
pounds attached to them 
the rye board of selectmen in 1984 licensed three poles in the 
town the new hampshire department of transportation also authorized 
poles on state highways including state roads that pass through rye 
the board of selectmen then changed its mind and sought to revoke 
the licenses a state judge ordered the poles removed but the new 
hampshire supreme court overruled the judge last march 
towns may not veto nuclear evacuation plans without good reason 
such as public safety the state supreme court said 
the state court said rye selectmen lack the authority to revoke 
the licenses they granted for any reason other than a reason 
relating to the safe free and convenient use for public travel of 
the highway the state court said the selectmen offered no 
justification based on safety for removing the poles 
the 56 billion seabrook plant has been a target of protests 
since before construction began in 1976 
it was completed in 1986 but has been unable to get a federal 
operating license federal regulators have yet to approve evacuation 
plans for communities surrounding seabrook including some in 
massachusetts 
there are also serious financial problems with public service of 
new hampshire having filed for bankruptcy protection in january 
the case is rye vs public service of new hampshire 88621 
