<TEXT>
sparkling white c130s with bright red 
crosses on their sides brought supplies to starving southern 
sudanese on monday in an airlift made possible by relaxed tensions 
in the countrys long civil war 
the airlift organized by the international committee of the red 
cross marked the first time since an antigovernment rebellion 
began in early 1983 that planes flew with guarantees from both sides 
that they wouldnt be shot at 
all of southern sudan an area as large as the state of texas is 
in the grip of famine caused by the war 
during the airlift which began sunday and is openended planes 
flew from khartoum to governmentheld wau the main town of the 
southern bahr elghazal region 625 miles southwest of khartoum 
carrying sorghum butter cooking oil and medical supplies they 
also flew from a kenyan border post to towns under control of the 
sudan peoples liberation army 
simultaneously an operation sponsored by agencies of the united 
nations and the sudanese government also was under way ferrying 
relief on smaller planes to aweil a governmentheld town north of 
wau officials said it too had guarantees from both sides 
western diplomats and un and other relief officials agreed the 
airlifts resulted from a slight relaxation of tensions between the 
two sides in the bitter war 
the clearest evidence is an interim peace agreement signed 
between rebel chieftain john garang and the spiritual leader of the 
ruling coalitions junior partner the democratic unionist party 
the agreement led to a flurry of contacts between the government and 
rebels trying to convene a constitutional convention by the end of 
this month 
despite the green light given by both sides officials said crews 
of the hercules cargo planes were under orders to fly at over 14000 
feet out of the range of rebel gunners and to make circuitous 
landing approaches 
the crew was tense on the first day but everything went all 
right one relief official said monday the planes landed okay 
in wau today as well 
until now prime minister sadek elmahdis government had refused 
to approve any airlifts to rebelheld places 
similarly the sudan peoples liberation army has accused the 
government of using civilian and relief planes to transport military 
equipment they have shot down at least three civilian planes 
killing more than 73 civilians and air traffic over the south has 
been limited almost completely to military aircraft 
preliminary reports from the area indicate the populations of 
both governmentheld towns and those in rebel hands which had 
swelled immensely because of displaced people have begun to shrink 
since the rainy season ended in october 
a un relief official said movement was more difficult during 
the rainy season and the army holds more control over the 
countryside after the rains 
another unfortunate factor is that a lot of these people have 
already died the official said it is never too late but we 
are pretty late 
there are no more daily deaths but we are also about two 
months too late to see the real tragedy another relief official 
said of the town of aweil 
western relief officials estimate at least 260000 people have 
died this year alone as they sought refuge from the fighting 
in 1988 only a few drops of relief went to the south and 
thats why the death toll was so steep one official said we 
hope this breakthrough will open the door for other agencies to go 
in 
all western diplomats and relief workers interviewed refused to 
give their names because of the governments sensitivity about the 
operation and the war 
officials close to the red cross airlift said organizers plan to 
continue the relief effort assuming the security arrangements hold 
until 10000 tons of relief food warehoused in port sudan on the 
countrys red sea coast are distributed 
the kenyan part of the operation is working from lokichokio just 
south of the sudanese border sending food to several rebelheld 
towns on smaller planes 
red cross officials have not divulged the cost of the operation 
but other sources said it is about 2 million the red cross is 
expected to launch an international appeal soon to collect money to 
continue the airlift 
