<TEXT>
beijing is officially turning to the right despite 
the governments leftist ideology 
municipal traffic officials already have banned left turns at 150 
intersections in an effort to reduce snarls and plan to outlaw all 
left turns everywhere in the capital by the end of 1989 the 
official china daily said monday 
to ensure there will be no turning back from the rightist course 
the city will be designating almost all streets oneway only the 
paper said 
although hardly any chinese have their own cars growing numbers 
of offices and enterprises are buying vehicles roads once used 
mainly by bicyclists are jammed daily by cars trucks jeeps and 
threewheeled vehicles of all kinds that creep at an average pace of 
about 12 mph 
the china daily quoted traffic officials as saying the 
rightturnonly policy already has reduced jams at intersections 
where it is enforced 
an informal poll of taxi drivers however say rigid rightism 
applied to traffic makes no more sense than extreme leftism did in 
the 1960s when revolutionaryminded officials decided to make red 
stand for go and green for stop in traffic lights 
traffic officials have not created alternate means for drivers to 
get to their leftward destinations such as overpasses instead 
most drivers turn right and then try to turn around in the side 
road creating little jams of cars making uturns 
