<DOCNO> AP881205-0170 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
three news organizations filed suit monday to 
force the bipartisan national economic commission to meet in public 
when it discusses economic forecasts and ways to cut the federal 
budget 
the lawsuit filed in federal court seeks an injunction to bar the 
commission from closing its scheduled dec 12 meeting to the public 
the suit contends that a secret proceeding would violate a federal 
openmeeting law 
the commission scheduled the closed session to discuss which 
economic forecast to adopt as a basis for making future 
recommendations and to review various budgetcutting options 
if the commission is permitted to deny the public access to its 
discussion of economic assumptions and its review of budget options 
the public will be deprived of an essential tool of democracy 
said the lawsuit by the washington post the wall street journal and 
the bureau of national affairs which publishes financial 
newsletters 
the lawsuit was also joined by consumer advocate ralph naders 
public citizen and stephen wildstrom an editor for business week 
it seeks a temporary restraining order to prevent the commission 
from holding the dec 12 meeting in private and a declaration that 
closed sessions violate the federal advisory committee act 
us district judge joyce hens green scheduled a hearing for 10 
am wednesday 
the commission held three socalled briefing sessions last summer 
without a quorum of the 12member panel present in order to avoid 
the openmeeting requirements officials discontinued that practice 
after objections were raised 
but alexander platt the commissions general counsel said the 
panel intended to go ahead with the closed session on dec 12 he 
said it was covered under a section of law that allows such 
discussions to be private if premature disclosure of the 
deliberations would frustrate an agencys actions 
we believe we understand the proper application of the federal 
advisory committee act and we have followed every appropriate 
procedure in closing the meeting we intend to hold the closed 
session on dec 12 he said 
jim hildreth spokesman for the commission said that the 
advisory panel was also worried that financial markets could be 
affected by partial news reports on the deliberations 
platt cited this concern to the plaintiffs in a letter that 
referred to a sharp drop in the financial markets following the nov 
16 appearance of federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan the 
complaint said 
greenspans recommendation that the president take urgent steps 
to reduce the federal deficit was cited by some observers as a cause 
of the drop in the stock market 
the complaint said the news organizations are particularly 
interested in the commissions discussion of economic assumptions 
becuse it will greatly influence if not determine what the 
commission forecasts for the national economy 
the commission has also scheduled an open meeting on wednesday to 
hear witnesses from the congressional budget office discuss the 
economic assumptions they will provide congress 
</TEXT>
