<TEXT>
a former associate of political maverick 
lyndon larouche testified monday that larouche exhorted his 
followers to raise large sums of money to help him save humanity 
from nuclear destruction and berated those who failed to meet 
fundraising quotas as suffering sexual impotence 
steven j bardwell also described a boiler room fundraising 
operation in larouches los angeles office as the mail and tax fraud 
conspiracy trial of the perennial presidential candidate entered its 
third week in us district court 
wayne hintz a former national finance officer for the larouche 
organization testified later that at his urging the organizations 
executive committee left the impression in april 1985 it would 
allocate 80000 per week to increased repayment of outstanding 
loans but hintz said the actual funds received for that purpose 
never exceeded about 38000 weekly 
meanwhile hintz said the total debt was growing because of new 
borrowing he said the debt rose from about 10 million in late 1984 
to 40 million by late 1985 with 45 million in total interest 
owed 
bardwell former editor of fusion magazine a larouche 
publication said larouche outlined his fundraising philosophy 
before enthusiastic followers in a speech in the bronx ny in 
january 1984 
bardwell said larouche demanded tremendous amounts of money 
to finance his speaking tours and television appearances and to 
provide protection against assassination attempts he justified 
any means short of thievery and thuggery to raise this money 
bardwell said 
he said the human race was on the verge of selfdestruction 
said bardwell who was associated with larouche for nearly 12 years 
he said they lacked the moral fiber to survive 
larouche said the human race would be destroyed by nuclear war if 
sufficient money were not raised to finance his operations bardwell 
said he compared the human race to lemmings rushing to their own 
destruction 
in every speech bardwell said larouche said the main reason 
some of his followers were failing to meet their fundraising quotas 
was sexual impotence or sexual problems and he frequently 
referred to them as swine 
bardwell said larouche berated organizers who hadnt raised 
enough money for contributing to the likelihood that he and his 
wife would be assassinated 
bardwell of hastings on hudson ny who resigned from the 
larouche organization in february 1984 because of a dispute over 
defense policy and money questions said he complained frequently to 
larouche about diversion of money raised from subscriptions to 
bardwells magazine a publication of the larouchesponsored fusion 
energy foundation 
he said larouche responded that bardwells sense of obligation to 
his subscribers was misplaced and that whether or not they 
knew it they had contributed money to support lyndon larouche and 
his ideas 
larouche also said his personal security took precedence over all 
other demands on his organizations revenues 
larouche and six associates are charged with mail fraud and 
conspiracy for allegedly raising more than 30 million in loans with 
no intention of repaying them 
larouche is charged separately with conspiring to defraud the 
internal revenue service by having all his personal expenses paid 
from funds of various corporations he controls prosecutors say 
larouche has not filed any federal income tax returns since 1978 
larouche has denied any wrongdoing and complained that he is the 
victim of government harassment if convicted on all 13 counts 
against him larouche faces a maximum penalty of 65 years in prison 
and fines totaling 325 million 
larouches codefendants who face lesser sentences if convicted 
of the mail fraud and conspiracy charges are william wertz his 
chief fundraiser chief legal adviser edward spannaus and 
fundraisers michael billington dennis small paul greenberg and 
joyce rubinstein 
bardwell testified that when he visited larouches los angeles 
office in 1983 he saw several rooms which larouche had called 
boiler rooms where telephone solicitors worked 10 hours to 12 
hours a day trying to meet team quotas of 600 to 700 daily 
the fundraising effort was very closely monitored by will 
wertz who posted periodic reports from the main office shopping 
centers and the los angeles airport on a bulletin board on his wall 
bardwell said larouche was highly pleased by the success of his los 
angeles fundraisers who were the best in the country 
in other testimony celia landegger of bronxville ny said she 
gave larouche solicitors 45000 in loans over a oneyear period 
ending in november 1985 but never had been repaid except for 
interest payments totaling 1300 
she said ms rubinstein at one point extended the payment 
deadline until january 1987 two years after the initial loan was 
supposed to be repaid but no payments were received 
</TEXT>
