<TEXT>
a special national institutes of health 
advisory committee formalized on monday its finding that it is 
acceptable for the federal government to back medical research 
involving the transplant of tissue from intentionally aborted fetal 
tissue 
the 16member panel spent a full day refining the wording of a 
lengthy report drafted in two earlier meetings however no 
substantive changes were made and the final report like earlier 
drafts carefully avoided taking a position on the morality of 
abortion itself or the morality of using tissue from such legally 
performed procedures 
there was no recorded vote on the key question of whether to 
recommend fetal tissue research but rather a series of separate 
votes taken on final wording of various subsections of the report 
however the tally at an oct 21 meeting had been 133 in favor 
of recommending that fetal tissue research proceed that specific 
question had been the focus of that meeting that sentiment was 
reflected in a minority report written by the same three dissenting 
members and made part of the final document under the heading 
additional comments 
the recommendation now goes to a standing nih advisory committee 
that is meeting dec 14 that committee in turn will make its 
recommendation to nih director james wyngaarden 
researchers hope that transplanting fetal brain cells into the 
brains of people with diabetes and parkinsons disease could provide 
an effective treatment perhaps in three to five years and that 
more study could lead to similar treatments for a number of other 
serious diseases for which no cure has been found 
the panels recommendation contains a number of guidelines to 
guard against women being encouraged even subtly to have an 
abortion in order to provide fetal tissue for research 
for example the committee said there should be no payment for 
the tissue beyond actual costs and that donations of fetal tissue 
to a family member or acquaintance should be banned lest women be 
tempted to become pregnant just so they could conceive a fetus for 
subsequent abortion and research use 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

