<TEXT>
soviet inspectors monitoring us compliance 
with the intermediate nuclear forces treaty watched monday while the 
first two out of 400 pershing ii missile motors were destroyed at an 
army facility east of here 
calm wind caused a 25minute delay before the first solidfuel 
missile motor was ignited on the sagebrushcovered plains at 1025 
am said army spokeswoman susan voss at the pueblo depot activity 
the colorado department of health permit that allows the rocket 
motors to be destroyed here requires winds of at least 4 mph out of 
the west to dissipate the rockets exhaust plume and drive it away 
from the city of pueblo 
ten soviet inspectors witnessed the first event along with 40 
news reporters and 60 vips voss said 
a total of nine missile motors are scheduled for destruction this 
week and nine more next week in the first phase of the threeyear 
program 
the soviet team leader was very happy to see the treaty was in 
effect he was very pleased with the way the elimination was handled 
and the way it went today voss said 
she said the missile motor burned approximately 56 seconds and 
completely eliminated the rocket motors solid propellant 
the second missile motor was fired at 101 pm and burned for 
606 seconds an army spokesman said 
voss said the army also is doing air monitoring for hydrogen 
chloride in compliance with the state permit 
the pershings were the delivery systems for europeanbased 
nuclear warheads aimed at the soviet union under terms of the inf 
treaty that took effect june 1 the united states has two years to 
destroy 450 of the missiles each of which is propelled by two 
rocket motors 
in exchange the soviet union will destroy a larger number of its 
intermediaterange missiles as us inspection teams look on 
pershing missiles have been destroyed at the longhorn army 
ammunition plant near marshall texas since sept 8 but this is the 
first destruction under soviet inspection to occur at the depot here 
the colorado health department after a long environmental 
review gave the army permission to conduct the burns for three 
years no more than six rockets can be burned per day 
