<TEXT>
a us supreme court justice refused monday 
to block the murder trial of a christian scientist couple accused of 
killing their diabetic daughter by withholding medical care 
william and christine hermanson citing a state law that parents 
following their faith may not be convicted of child abuse simply by 
denying medical care sought to block their prosecution on grounds 
of religious freedom 
justice anthony m kennedy denied the emergency request without 
comment early monday the day the trial was due to begin 
after kennedy issued his ruling sarasota circuit judge alan 
dakan granted a defense motion to delay the trial until jan 23 to 
allow publicity about the case to die down 
the hermansons are charged with thirddegree murder and child 
abuse in the september 1986 death of their 7yearold daughter amy 
the couple denied her insulin injections because their religion 
teaches reliance on prayer instead of medical treatment 
amy had been ill for eight days and her diabetes worsened before 
an anonymous complaint alerted authorities a court ordered medical 
intervention but the girl was dead when paramedics arrived at the 
hermansons home 
when a request to keep the case from being tried was turned down 
by the florida supreme court the hermansons filed a similar motion 
before the nations high court 
the florida law which exempts parents from child abuse charges 
for denying medical care on religious grounds still allows the court 
to order medical intervention if the childs health is at risk 
prosecutors tried to have the law declared unconstitutional but 
a circuit judge upheld the state law allowing the hermansons to use 
the law as a defense 
assistant state attorney pat whitaker said earlier this year that 
while the law may provide some defense on the child abuse count it 
is irrelevant to the murder charge 
the emotional nature of the case was noted by dakan who ruled 
last month that certain statements in the court file may be sealed 
the case may involve serious and controversial questions of 
religious beliefs dakan said publication of such material 
could seriously hinder the defendants ability to obtain a fair 
and impartial trial 
