<TEXT>
the banjo an instrument that traveled to 
america with african slaves has captured the imagination of pickers 
with dozens of playing styles who perform almost every type of music 
somebody whos a nonbanjo player might think all banjo playing 
is alike said art rosenbaum who researches banjo music but 
theres so much way to express your individuality through banjo 
banjo performers today range from snuffy jenkins who learned his 
threefinger picking style in the 1920s to tony trischka who has 
teamed the banjo with symphony orchestras and electronic 
synthesizers 
elements of bluegrass are combined with rock n roll jazz and 
classical music on the three albums by trischka he has performed in 
tuxedo with a symphony orchestra 
a lot of people were kind of like bent out of shape about it 
they said you cant do that with the banjo i just want to get 
into as much of the banjo as i can explore trischka said 
the instrument itself has evolved and playing styles have 
evolved said rosenbaum a picker who has uses his research on the 
instrument and folk traditions in radio shows and books rosenbaum 
joined more than 150 other players at a series of workshops in 
lebanon this fall 
the first banjos were crafted from gourds in africa he said 
later in america they were made with a wooden frame and animal hide 
stretched across the head 
they used to be made of cat skin in the old days and they used 
catgut for strings rosenbaum said they say that when someone 
wanted a banjo they would just go out and kill a cat and in two 
hours they would be playing a tune on it 
some of the earliest banjo performances were 19th century 
minstrel shows where white performers mimicked the banjo playing of 
blacks and painted their faces with black makeup 
some people still play in the tradition of the minstrels and 
from that style grew the classic banjo practiced today by british 
recording artist chris sands and others sands plays ragtime and 
also arranges the music of bach handel and chopin for the banjo 
a friend of mine says nothing ever disappears i guess 
thats kind of true with the banjo rosenbaum said 
oldtime banjo playing remains popular including the 
clawhammer style a rhythmic method of striking downward on the 
strings that was revived during the folk craze of the 60s he said 
todays bluegrass relies heavily on threefinger picking made 
famous in the 50s by the father of bluegrass banjo earl scruggs 
as a member of the foggy mountain boys 
scruggs style evolved from threefinger picking first put on the 
radio by jenkins in 1934 jenkins continues to perform the folk 
tunes he learned as a boy although he says playing is more 
difficult at age 80 
i cant feel the strings anymore he said it makes my 
heart sick at my stomach to see other guys picking and want to but i 
cant 
jenkins says he didnt invent threefinger picking and he 
doesnt consider himself a bluegrass player i dont claim to be a 
bluegrass picker because that term came out after me and im too 
old to change i dont think its bluegrass that different its 
just the oldtime music speeded up 
traditional bluegrass epitomized by the foggy mountain boys 
tune foggy mountain breakdown and often thought of as 
hillbilly music is by far the most popular banjo style said janet 
deering coowner of deering banjo co in lemon grove calif 
only about 10 percent of us banjo pickers play the fourstring 
banjos used primarily for dixieland jazz she said most banjos have 
five strings 
deering estimates that about 2000 banjos costing from 500 to 
thousands of dollars are made in the united states each year 
hundreds more mostly less expensive are imported 
no statistics on the number of banjos or banjo players are kept 
she said 
i would guess compared to guitar players youd have one banjo 
player to every 100 guitar players deering said but there are 
millions playing the guitar 
a growing number of musicians are experimenting with new 
directions for the banjo and deerings company began making an 
electric banjo about 1 years ago and 100 have been sold 
</TEXT>
