mothers of babies with severe head and 
facial deformities cuddle and smile at them less than those with 
normal infants but claim greater satisfaction from parenthood a 
new study suggests 
the researchers made 18minute videotapes of 10 mothers and their 
4monthold babies five of whom were normal and five of whom 
suffered from disorders producing serious deformities but no 
neurological or mental deficiencies the infants were matched in 
terms of age sex birth order all firstborn ethnic status and 
the mothers age marital status and education 
the sessions included 10 minutes of play five minutes in which 
the mothers tried to get their babies to vocalize and three minutes 
of babies facetoface with their mothers who had to imitate the 
babies expressions and actions 
mothers of deformed babies touched them a fifth as much as 
mothers of normal infants spent a third as much time demonstrating 
toys to them and smiled or laughed at them half has much said r 
christopher barden a university of utah psychologist who directed 
the study 
in turn the deformed infants touched their mothers and smiled or 
laughed at them a fourth as much as the normal babies cried more 
than twice as much and responded to their mothers voice a fifth as 
much barden found 
the mothers of deformed children however claimed greater 
satisfaction with parenthood suggesting they are either unwilling 
to admit or unaware of the difficulties and stress imposed by their 
deformed child he said 
braden collaborated with martin e ford of stanford university 
and kenneth salyer marcy rogerssalyer and gayle jensen of the 
