<TEXT>
the nations economy continued to grow in 
november but at a slightly slower pace than the previous month a 
study of corporate purchasing executives found 
the national association of purchasing management which tracks 
the strength of the economy with a monthly survey of purchasing 
executives said sunday that its purchasing managers index dipped to 
566 percent from octobers 568 percent 
but the index still indicated the economy continued to be robust 
a reading above 50 indicates the economy is generally expanding 
while a reading of less than 50 indicates the economy is contracting 
the purchasing managers who took part in the survey said 
production continued to increase last month but at a slightly 
slower clip than in october 
twentyseven percent of the respondents reported production was 
up compared with 26 percent in october fiftyeight percent 
compared with octobers 65 percent said production was the same 
but 15 percent said production was slower compared with 9 percent 
the previous month 
employment was sharply higher in november eighteen percent of 
the respondents reported higher employment while 69 percent said it 
was the same and 13 percent said it was down that compared with 16 
percent reporting higher employment during october 72 percent 
reporting it was the same and 12 percent reporting it fell 
the purchasing managers also reported new orders grew in november 
thirty percent of the respondents said their companies had more 
new orders last month while 52 percent reported orders were the 
same and 18 percent said orders were down that compared with 28 
percent reporting orders up in october 54 percent saying they were 
the same and 18 percent saying they were down 
vendor deliveries which indicate whether companies are getting 
orders faster than they can fill them were again slow in november 
but picked up some speed from october eleven percent of the 
purchasing managers said deliveries were slower in november 
compared with 17 percent the previous month 
eightyone percent said deliveries were running at the same rate 
compared with 77 percent in october eight percent said they were 
faster compared with octobers 6 percent 
inventories increased last month seventeen percent of the 
purchasing managers said their inventories were higher 61 percent 
said they were the same and 22 percent said they were lower in 
october 15 percent reported they were higher 65 percent said they 
were the same and 20 percent said they were lower 
prices continued to rise with 40 percent of the respondents 
saying they were paying more for goods 58 percent saying they were 
the same and 2 percent saying they were lower in october 45 
percent said they were higher 51 percent said prices were the same 
and 4 percent said they were lower 
the national association of purchasing management which 
represents puchasing executives nationwide said it questioned 
managers in more than 250 industrial companies for its survey 
</TEXT>
