drexel burnham lambert inc the investment giant 
under investigation for more than two years has told employees that 
negotiations with federal prosecutors have reached a crucial 
stage and the firm may either face racketeering indictments or 
plead guilty to lesser charges soon 
chief executive frederick joseph outlined the status of drexels 
crisis in a memorandum to the staff last week copies were leaked to 
the wall street journal and new york times and sources familiar 
with the letter confirmed the contents of the memo today 
a guilty plea would mark a stunning turnaround for drexel which 
vowed to fight accusations of securities fraud that arose after 
speculator ivan f boesky implicated the firm in a plea bargain he 
reached with the government 
boesky who had extensive dealings with drexel paid a record 
100 million in fines and penalties for insider trading and is now 
serving a threeyear prison term for conspiracy to lie to the 
securities and exchange commission 
drexel was named in a sec civil securities fraud complaint nearly 
three months ago and us attorney rudolph giuliani has been 
supervising a grand jury investigation of the firm 
in recent weeks we have had discussions with the government 
which are now reaching a crucial stage joseph told employees in 
the memo 
if drexel does not agree to settlement terms with giuliani the 
memo read we believe that he intends to indict the firm as well 
as certain of our employees and to include in such an indictment 
socalled racketeering charges 
conviction under the racketeer influenced and corrupt 
organizations law which originally was intended to combat drug 
pushers and pimps would taint drexel as a criminal enterprise and 
could entail crippling fines 
if we settle we can put this constant attack on the firm 
behind us joseph said in the memo but to do so will require a 
guilty plea we believe however that the us attorney would not 
accept a settlement from drexel unless it exceeds boeskys 
settlement 
he estimated that as a result of the investigation the firm 
already had lost 15 billion in potential revenues spent 175 
million in direct legal expenses and provided 15 million pages of 
governmentrequested documents 
joseph said any settlement likely would involve what he called a 
substantial dollar amount and a guilty plea by the firm as well 
as other conditions 
drexel spokesman steven anreder declined to comment officials at 
giulianis office also declined to comment in accordance with their 
practice of confidentiality about criminal investigations 
the journal quoting sources it did not identify said drexel was 
leaning more toward a settlement because of several recent 
developments notably subpoenas to drexel attorneys from giulianis 
office and his attempts to compel cooperation from a senior employee 
to substantiate the governments case 
