<TEXT>
urban water system managers have taken limited 
action in response to the greenhouse effect say a panel of 
scientists who on monday urged the managers to seek scientific 
advice 
urban water managers say they are not going to act and you 
cant blame them until they see it with their own eyes or the 
professional bodies are in agreement said paul e waggoner 
cochairman of a committee on climate and the management of us 
water resources convened by the american association for the 
advancement of science 
waggoner is also director of the connecticut agricultural 
experiment station at new haven 
interviews with officials at nine water systems found only one 
minor action taken out of concern for the warming of the earth or 
the greenhouse effect the relocation of a discharge pipe in 
new york city 
among the committees recommendations were organizations of 
professional water resource managers should meet formally and 
regularly with scientists concerned with water and climate change 
the report also said practical managers must decide upon 
actions now with consequences several decades hence after some 
expected climatic changes have occurred 
the report did not identify the water system managers interviewed 
but said some of them were located in the district of columbia new 
york massachusetts indiana louisiana utah and arizona 
the scientists found in their interviews that overall the most 
immediate concern encountered was for the effect of a rising sea 
level on supply whereas effects of climate change on drainage 
health and disposal of waste evoked little concern 
the socalled greenhouse effect is the overall average warming of 
the earth because of the buildup of gases in the atmosphere that 
trap radiant heat of the planet that normally would be radiated out 
to space many scientists say it already has begun 
one effect of the process would be the expansion of the oceans 
and a rise in sea level simply from the warmer water 
the water resources panel used widely accepted computer 
predictions of an increase in average global temperature of three to 
eight degrees fahrenheit sometime in the next century 
these computer models predict an increase in worldwide annual 
average precipitation of 7 percent to 15 percent but there is 
little agreement among them on what could happen to particular 
regions the panel said regions could see average temperatures rise 
by as much as 18 degrees or fall by more than five degrees 
regionally precipitation could show anything from a 20 percent 
decrease to a 20 percent increase and runoff could rise 50 percent 
or fall 50 percent evaporation from vegetation and other sources 
could increase by 10 percent or fall by the same amount 
sea level increase could be between 4 inches and 3 feet the 
scientists said 
among other recommendations the panel called for measures to 
encourage markets in water rights emphasis on research on regional 
effects within the next decades as opposed to shorter or longer 
periods and awareness of the opportunities for conserving water and 
adding flexibility to water delivery systems 
